WEBVTT

00:01.460 --> 00:10.670
♪♪

00:10.670 --> 00:12.330
I know it's Christmas,
Mom,

00:12.330 --> 00:14.420
but I think you have to
stay home with Dad.

00:14.420 --> 00:18.080
He needs you
to take care of him right now.

00:18.080 --> 00:19.290
I'm sad, too.

00:20.620 --> 00:22.420
Bye, Mom.

00:22.420 --> 00:24.670
[ Cellphone thuds ]

00:24.670 --> 00:26.290
What's with
the happy dance?

00:26.290 --> 00:28.040
Remember how
my dad's foot surgery

00:28.040 --> 00:29.460
was supposed to be healed
by now?

00:29.460 --> 00:30.670
It did, but great news.

00:30.670 --> 00:32.670
The bone set wrong,
and they had to rebreak it.

00:32.670 --> 00:33.880
How lucky is that?

00:33.880 --> 00:35.210
You're a regular
Clara Barton.

00:35.210 --> 00:37.460
It's not an insult if I don't
know who you're talking about.

00:37.460 --> 00:38.250
True.

00:38.250 --> 00:39.670
I'm gonna miss my dad,

00:39.670 --> 00:41.750
but with my mother
not being here,

00:41.750 --> 00:43.330
I will finally be able
to make

00:43.330 --> 00:45.830
my Nana's Bavarian Meat Tree
with Taylor.

00:45.830 --> 00:47.330
What are you
signing me up for?

00:47.330 --> 00:49.330
It's this tradition
I always did with her.

00:49.330 --> 00:50.960
It's a mini Christmas tree

00:50.960 --> 00:53.670
made of sausage,
lunch meats, and meatballs.

00:53.670 --> 00:56.170
For Christmas this year,
I want to not do that.

00:56.170 --> 00:58.420
You're gonna love it
so much!

00:58.420 --> 01:00.330
If it's so great,
then why'd you stop doing it?

01:00.330 --> 01:02.380
After Nana died,
my mother banned it.

01:02.380 --> 01:04.620
With your parents not coming
and my parents not coming,

01:04.620 --> 01:06.830
it's just gonna be us.
Mm.

01:06.830 --> 01:08.960
You still haven't talked
to Grandpa? It's been two years.

01:08.960 --> 01:11.420
Well, since he told me he had
a second family in England

01:11.420 --> 01:13.170
and I have a brother
that I've never met --

01:13.170 --> 01:14.460
also named Greg --

01:14.460 --> 01:15.830
Are we allowed
to laugh at that yet?

01:15.830 --> 01:17.380
No!

01:17.380 --> 01:19.330
Anyway, I haven't really
been in the mood

01:19.330 --> 01:21.540
to call up my parents
and see what's shakin'.

01:21.540 --> 01:23.830
I'm sorry, Dad.

01:23.830 --> 01:25.500
It's a little weird
that it's Christmas

01:25.500 --> 01:27.290
and there's
no other family coming.

01:27.290 --> 01:28.670
It's kind of depressing,
actually.

01:28.670 --> 01:31.420
All I know is,
less relatives means less gifts.

01:31.420 --> 01:33.830
You mean "fewer" relatives
means "fewer" gifts.

01:33.830 --> 01:36.460
Hey, Dad?
Literally no one cares.

01:36.460 --> 01:38.540
Speaking of gifts,
I got you

01:38.540 --> 01:40.330
the perfect Greg Otto gift
this year.

01:40.330 --> 01:42.210
I put a lot of thought
into it.

01:42.210 --> 01:44.000
I didn't just give you
the Starbucks gift card

01:44.000 --> 01:45.620
that I forgot to give
Anna-Kat's teacher.

01:45.620 --> 01:46.670
I can't wait.

01:46.670 --> 01:48.040
Maybe this won't be so bad.

01:48.040 --> 01:49.500
Maybe less family
means less drama.

01:49.500 --> 01:52.460
Don't you mean "fewer" family
means "fewer" drama?

01:52.460 --> 01:55.330
Anna-Kat:
Oliver, no! I made that!
Oliver: Get out of my face!

01:55.330 --> 01:57.460
Oliver,
what did you do?

01:57.460 --> 01:59.670
He broke the chimney
off my gingerbread house.

01:59.670 --> 02:01.170
It's food!

02:01.170 --> 02:02.830
I built that with Dad!

02:02.830 --> 02:04.420
You wrecked
the whole ventilation system.

02:04.420 --> 02:05.830
There's
a vanilla wafer furnace!

02:05.830 --> 02:07.710
Stop ruining
our drama-free Christmas!

02:07.710 --> 02:09.750
Now, go upstairs
and do something together.

02:09.750 --> 02:12.500
Without fighting,
or Christmas is canceled!

02:12.500 --> 02:14.330
Remember what we said
about making threats

02:14.330 --> 02:15.500
we can't
follow through on?

02:15.500 --> 02:16.540
Who are you to talk?

02:16.540 --> 02:17.920
You potty-trained
all three of them

02:17.920 --> 02:19.670
by threatening if they
didn't stop using diapers,

02:19.670 --> 02:20.960
Elmo would quit
show business.

02:20.960 --> 02:26.420
♪♪

02:26.420 --> 02:28.250
♪♪

02:29.330 --> 02:30.500
Hey, Mom.

02:30.500 --> 02:33.500
One sec. I'm tracking
Dad's surprise Christmas gift.

02:33.500 --> 02:35.540
It's exactly
what he needs this year.

02:35.540 --> 02:37.540
Don't ask what it is, because
I'm not going to tell you.

02:37.540 --> 02:39.420
I won't, because I have
zero interest.

02:39.420 --> 02:40.540
I'll tell you
if you guess.

02:40.540 --> 02:41.330
Fine.

02:41.330 --> 02:42.500
Uh...surfboard?

02:42.500 --> 02:43.580
That was
a terrible guess.

02:43.580 --> 02:45.170
It was better
when you didn't even care.

02:45.170 --> 02:47.000
Ehh.

02:47.000 --> 02:48.330
This is so much meat!

02:48.330 --> 02:51.960
I know! I'm handing down
the family meat-tree tradition.

02:51.960 --> 02:54.080
I can't believe
this is what I inherit.

02:54.080 --> 02:56.120
Don't you have
any jewelry?

02:56.120 --> 02:57.580
No, you get a meat tree.

02:57.580 --> 02:59.920
♪♪

02:59.920 --> 03:02.920
I'm sorry I ate your chimney,
so let me make it up to you.

03:05.920 --> 03:09.670
Wait. This is where Mom and Dad
hide all our presents?

03:09.670 --> 03:12.500
In their closet?
Not smart.

03:12.500 --> 03:15.750
Nope. We are fighting
an uphill battle genetically.

03:17.500 --> 03:19.500
Mine.

03:19.500 --> 03:20.620
Taylor's.

03:20.620 --> 03:21.580
Yours.

03:24.040 --> 03:26.920
Feels like another
junior-executive pencil set.

03:26.920 --> 03:28.380
What part of
"I'll just take the cash"

03:28.380 --> 03:29.960
do they not understand?

03:31.750 --> 03:33.790
Oh, this unwrapped one
has no card.

03:33.790 --> 03:35.500
It's probably for me.

03:35.500 --> 03:36.790
Says who?

03:36.790 --> 03:37.710
I do!

03:37.710 --> 03:38.710
[ Clank ]

03:38.710 --> 03:40.330
[ Gasps ]

03:40.330 --> 03:42.790
Oh, no! We broke
Mom's serving platter.

03:42.790 --> 03:44.620
Mom uses it
every Christmas.

03:44.620 --> 03:45.830
We're so dead.

03:45.830 --> 03:47.960
No one has to know.
I can fix this.

03:47.960 --> 03:49.830
How?
It's completely broken.

03:49.830 --> 03:52.000
Do you know how many things
I've broken in this house

03:52.000 --> 03:54.170
and glued back together
with no one noticing?

03:54.170 --> 04:01.750
♪♪

04:01.750 --> 04:03.750
I can fix this thing.
No problem.

04:03.750 --> 04:06.120
I don't think I could handle
seeing the disappointed look

04:06.120 --> 04:08.330
on Mom's face
if she found out we broke it.

04:08.330 --> 04:09.380
That would kill me.

04:09.380 --> 04:11.210
That's the beauty --
there's no guilt.

04:11.210 --> 04:13.250
Because I do such a great job
at fixing things,

04:13.250 --> 04:14.880
there are never
any consequences.

04:14.880 --> 04:17.710
Have you ever broken anything
of mine and not told me?

04:17.710 --> 04:18.500
Never.

04:18.500 --> 04:23.960
♪♪

04:25.250 --> 04:26.500
I don't believe you.

04:26.500 --> 04:28.000
Clever girl.

04:28.000 --> 04:31.000
♪♪

04:31.000 --> 04:33.040
Ugh.
This is so nasty.

04:33.040 --> 04:34.750
I can't get the meat rolls
to stick.

04:34.750 --> 04:37.380
I know. My grandmother
made it look easy.

04:37.380 --> 04:38.920
But we're making memories.

04:38.920 --> 04:39.920
Not good ones.

04:39.920 --> 04:41.040
[ Doorbell rings ]

04:41.040 --> 04:42.670
Nobody get the door
except Dad!

04:42.670 --> 04:44.880
Greg!
Your present's here!

04:46.080 --> 04:48.380
Maybe it's Amazon
with the "Big Book of
Shakespearean Insults"

04:48.380 --> 04:49.420
I asked for.

04:49.420 --> 04:50.920
"Methink'st thou art
a general offense

04:50.920 --> 04:52.670
and every man
should beat thee"!

04:52.670 --> 04:54.290
[ Chuckles ]

04:54.290 --> 04:55.250
Okay.

04:58.080 --> 04:59.670
[ British accent ] Hello.
Are you Greg Otto?

04:59.670 --> 05:00.830
Yeah.

05:00.830 --> 05:02.330
I'm Greg Otto, too.

05:02.330 --> 05:03.330
What's that, now?

05:03.330 --> 05:06.040
Greg, this is Greg,

05:06.040 --> 05:08.500
your half-brother
from your father's secret family

05:08.500 --> 05:10.040
all the way from England.

05:10.040 --> 05:13.670
I told you I got you
the perfect Greg Otto gift!

05:13.670 --> 05:15.330
You're my half-brother.

05:15.330 --> 05:17.040
But I'm going to give you
a full hug.

05:17.040 --> 05:18.580
[ Sleigh bells jingle ]

05:18.580 --> 05:20.580
[ Whispering ] I said
I wanted the Shakespeare book.

05:20.580 --> 05:21.580
Shakespeare!

05:21.580 --> 05:22.620
♪♪

05:22.620 --> 05:23.540
Brother!

05:27.420 --> 05:31.250
So, I bet you're wondering
how all of this happened, Greg.

05:31.250 --> 05:33.710
No, it's pretty clear
how this happened.

05:33.710 --> 05:35.750
I met a cute girl
when I was a TA,

05:35.750 --> 05:37.000
and now I'm here.

05:37.000 --> 05:40.000
A few weeks back,
I found out from Father

05:40.000 --> 05:42.790
that I have a long-lost brother
in the Colonies.

05:42.790 --> 05:44.460
That means America.

05:44.460 --> 05:45.790
Everyone knows that.

05:45.790 --> 05:47.210
Well, that's
where you're wrong, Oliver,

05:47.210 --> 05:48.250
because I don't know that.

05:48.250 --> 05:50.040
Look at you,
making me feel stupid.

05:51.120 --> 05:53.120
Well, as luck would have it,
when I tracked you down,

05:53.120 --> 05:55.420
your lovely wife
happened to answer the phone.

05:55.420 --> 05:56.880
That was lucky.

05:56.880 --> 05:58.290
I'm a lucky guy.

05:58.290 --> 06:01.500
While we spoke, I mentioned
I was coming to lecture at Yale.

06:01.500 --> 06:03.120
And I said,
"Let's keep this a secret

06:03.120 --> 06:06.210
and have you come over as
a surprise gift for Christmas."

06:06.210 --> 06:08.500
British Gregs are flying
off the shelves this year.

06:08.500 --> 06:10.250
[ Laughter ]

06:10.250 --> 06:11.540
[ Forced chuckle ]

06:11.540 --> 06:13.670
It's so cool
we have a British uncle.

06:13.670 --> 06:15.540
Here.
What's this called?

06:15.540 --> 06:16.830
A biscuit.

06:16.830 --> 06:19.120
Aw, man, that is not
what we call it here at all.

06:19.120 --> 06:20.250
[ Chuckles ]

06:20.250 --> 06:22.210
Chiseled face,
charming accent.

06:22.210 --> 06:23.880
Would it be okay
if I called you "Dad"?

06:23.880 --> 06:24.830
Oliver!

06:24.830 --> 06:26.500
Shh, Greg.
I'm talking to my dad.

06:26.500 --> 06:28.420
So, uh...

06:28.420 --> 06:31.460
how did it come up with Father
that you have a brother?

06:31.460 --> 06:33.000
He told me
while he was in London

06:33.000 --> 06:35.080
for the Charles Dickens
Holiday Festival.

06:35.080 --> 06:37.120
We've gone together every year
since I was a boy.

06:37.120 --> 06:38.290
How nice.

06:38.290 --> 06:40.330
The only place he ever took me
was the travel agent

06:40.330 --> 06:42.080
so that he could buy
his plane tickets --

06:42.080 --> 06:44.000
[ Gasps ]

06:44.000 --> 06:45.670
...to England.

06:45.670 --> 06:46.790
Ah.

06:48.670 --> 06:50.420
Interesting tidbit --

06:50.420 --> 06:52.670
not only are you
both professors,

06:52.670 --> 06:54.790
but you're both authors,
too.

06:54.790 --> 06:58.170
That's right. Greg, I
read your John Stuart Mill
book on the plane.

06:58.170 --> 06:59.330
I absolutely loved it.

06:59.330 --> 07:00.460
Thank you.

07:04.670 --> 07:07.460
[ Whispering ] You need to say
something to him right now.

07:07.460 --> 07:09.210
Talk to him.
Say something!

07:11.170 --> 07:12.710
What's your book about?

07:12.710 --> 07:14.000
Books, technically.

07:14.000 --> 07:16.580
It's a series of novels
about the Norman Conquest.

07:17.710 --> 07:18.880
A series? Wow.

07:18.880 --> 07:21.670
I mean, don't feel obligated
to read it.

07:21.670 --> 07:22.790
It's a lot.

07:22.790 --> 07:24.620
Uh, just wait for it
to come out in theaters.

07:24.620 --> 07:26.000
Unless you don't like
George Clooney.

07:26.000 --> 07:27.290
Then just skip it.

07:27.290 --> 07:28.580
Dad, this is crazy.

07:28.580 --> 07:30.120
Uncle Greg
is exactly like you,

07:30.120 --> 07:31.710
only the way-better
version.

07:31.710 --> 07:34.000
What an astute
observation, son.

07:34.000 --> 07:35.170
No, seriously.

07:35.170 --> 07:36.500
He's Restoration Hardware,

07:36.500 --> 07:38.670
and you're whatever
discount brand this couch is.

07:39.750 --> 07:42.750
Katie, could you help me change
the toner on the printer?

07:42.750 --> 07:43.920
Why don't you ask
Oliver --

07:43.920 --> 07:45.540
It needs to be you,
and it needs to be now.

07:49.170 --> 07:50.540
Is...?

07:50.540 --> 07:53.420
So, if you're looking for
the bathroom, what do you say?

07:53.420 --> 07:54.670
"Which way to the loo?"

07:54.670 --> 07:55.880
Amazing.

07:55.880 --> 07:57.620
Clear your Monday.
I'm taking you to show-and-tell.

07:57.620 --> 07:58.620
Ah, okay.

08:00.670 --> 08:02.880
Just wondering out loud,
but what made you think

08:02.880 --> 08:04.670
for the holidays,
I would want a visit

08:04.670 --> 08:06.580
from my father's
illegitimate love child?

08:06.580 --> 08:08.000
Well, I asked
Doris and Angela,

08:08.000 --> 08:09.790
and they said
I definitely should.

08:09.790 --> 08:12.330
Definitely don't do that.
That is the worst idea
I've ever heard.

08:12.330 --> 08:14.830
Mm...you know what?
I'm gonna do it.

08:14.830 --> 08:16.290
I just thought
it would be nice for you

08:16.290 --> 08:17.500
to have more family
in your life

08:17.500 --> 08:19.040
since you stopped talking
to your parents.

08:19.040 --> 08:20.500
I don't need more family
in my life,

08:20.500 --> 08:22.500
and I don't need you
meddling in my business.

08:22.500 --> 08:24.830
That's a wife's job.
I'm mucking around in your pond.

08:24.830 --> 08:27.290
What?
Your pond.
Your emotional pond.

08:27.290 --> 08:30.500
What does that mean?
On the surface, a pond
is still and tranquil.

08:30.500 --> 08:31.670
You got to get down
to the bottom

08:31.670 --> 08:33.000
and bring
all the bad stuff up.

08:33.000 --> 08:34.120
Why would you
want to do that?!

08:34.120 --> 08:35.500
To heal?
I don't know.

08:35.500 --> 08:37.750
I don't write the Lifetime
movies, Greg. I just watch them.

08:37.750 --> 08:41.460
Now, listen -- I love you,
and I'm trying to help you.

08:41.460 --> 08:43.830
So go out there
and appreciate it.

08:43.830 --> 08:45.000
Fine.

08:47.170 --> 08:48.290
But for the record,

08:48.290 --> 08:50.330
are we really sure
he is who he says he is?

08:50.330 --> 08:51.500
He could be grifting us.

08:51.500 --> 08:52.750
I'll be sure to lock up

08:52.750 --> 08:54.500
our collection
of ketchup packets.

08:59.500 --> 09:02.120
Look! Uncle Greg figured out how
to make the meat rolls stick.

09:02.120 --> 09:03.750
I spent a little time
in Bavaria.

09:03.750 --> 09:05.580
I know my way
around a meat tree.

09:05.580 --> 09:06.710
What were you
doing there?

09:06.710 --> 09:08.960
I guess just being handsome
and younger than me.

09:10.580 --> 09:19.000
♪♪

09:19.000 --> 09:27.500
♪♪

09:27.500 --> 09:29.170
Looks good.

09:29.170 --> 09:30.170
Fan me.

09:30.170 --> 09:32.330
♪♪

09:32.330 --> 09:34.170
[ Click, whirring ]

09:34.170 --> 09:35.250
What do we do now?

09:35.250 --> 09:36.830
We'll wait for it to dry.

09:36.830 --> 09:39.330
In the meantime, we'll go
downstairs and act natural.

09:39.330 --> 09:41.080
I don't like
lying to Mom.

09:41.080 --> 09:43.000
It's not a lie.
It's a cover-up.

09:43.000 --> 09:45.000
Like how the moon landing
was filmed on a soundstage

09:45.000 --> 09:46.170
in Arizona?

09:47.380 --> 09:49.000
The Internet
is not good for you.

09:49.000 --> 09:50.750
Katie: I'm just grabbing
Nana's platter.

09:50.750 --> 09:52.830
[ Click, whirring stops ]
Then I'm coming right back
to meat tree it up!

09:52.830 --> 09:55.040
She's coming up for the platter.
We're so busted!

09:56.080 --> 09:57.380
Relax.

09:57.380 --> 09:59.170
We'll do that thing
where we fight in front of her

09:59.170 --> 10:00.460
and she gets annoyed
and then forgets

10:00.460 --> 10:03.290
what she was gonna do
in the first place.

10:03.290 --> 10:04.830
[ Drawer opens ]

10:07.580 --> 10:09.040
Follow me.

10:12.290 --> 10:14.420
Mom, Oliver ate
all the M&M's

10:14.420 --> 10:16.380
out of my giant
Christmas candy cane.

10:16.380 --> 10:17.710
I didn't see
your name on it!

10:17.710 --> 10:19.380
My name is literally
written on it

10:19.380 --> 10:21.830
in huge, green,
sparkly letters!

10:21.830 --> 10:23.960
Well, maybe if you --
Hey, can you guys
please stop?

10:23.960 --> 10:26.420
All I want for Christmas
is for you two to get along.

10:26.420 --> 10:27.830
Is that too much to ask?

10:27.830 --> 10:29.080
No.
No.

10:29.080 --> 10:30.080
Thank you.

10:30.080 --> 10:31.960
Wait. Why did I
come up here?

10:31.960 --> 10:35.500
To ask us to come downstairs
and visit more with Uncle Greg?

10:35.500 --> 10:37.000
Oh, right!

10:37.000 --> 10:39.120
Don't take long.

10:39.120 --> 10:40.290
Whoa.

10:40.290 --> 10:41.960
You just controlled
her mind.

10:41.960 --> 10:44.380
You're like that fungus
that gets into an ant's brain,

10:44.380 --> 10:46.290
then makes the ant climb
to the top of a tree

10:46.290 --> 10:47.790
and then blows up
the ant's head

10:47.790 --> 10:50.500
so the fungal spores
go all over the forest.

10:51.750 --> 10:53.670
Yeah, I guess I am.

10:53.670 --> 10:56.500
♪♪

10:56.500 --> 10:58.080
Oh. Hey.

10:58.080 --> 10:59.170
Hope you don't mind.

10:59.170 --> 11:01.210
Just snooping around
your office a bit.

11:01.210 --> 11:04.170
Ah, these photos of your family
are lovely.

11:04.170 --> 11:06.250
All I have on my walls
are degrees and awards.

11:06.250 --> 11:07.330
[ Chuckles ]

11:07.330 --> 11:09.000
Yeah.
We all get it.

11:09.000 --> 11:11.000
You're the more successful
brother. Congrats.

11:11.000 --> 11:11.960
What?

11:11.960 --> 11:13.580
Oh, no,
you've got it all wrong.

11:13.580 --> 11:16.620
You've got the lovely wife
and the three amazing kids.

11:16.620 --> 11:18.460
I'm all alone.

11:18.460 --> 11:20.540
No, you're
the more successful brother.

11:20.540 --> 11:22.290
I am?

11:22.290 --> 11:24.040
That's why I came to America
so quickly

11:24.040 --> 11:26.750
when I found out
I had a sibling.

11:26.750 --> 11:29.540
I mean, the one thing
I've always wanted is a family.

11:29.540 --> 11:30.830
You never married?

11:30.830 --> 11:33.330
No, just a series
of vapid models,

11:33.330 --> 11:36.830
bouncing around from
nimble woman to nimble woman,

11:36.830 --> 11:37.920
most of them half my age.

11:37.920 --> 11:40.210
Let's move on
from your sad love life.

11:40.210 --> 11:42.580
But you understand
the importance of family.

11:42.580 --> 11:44.540
That's why I'm sure
you would've tracked me down

11:44.540 --> 11:46.000
as soon as you found out
about me,

11:46.000 --> 11:49.000
but Katie cooked up
this little surprise instead.

11:49.000 --> 11:51.920
[ Door opens, closes ]
Yeah. O-Of course.
I-I would've come running.

11:51.920 --> 11:54.540
Katie: Greg!
Can you come in here, please?

11:54.540 --> 11:55.670
Coming.
Coming.

11:55.670 --> 11:58.170
Oh, that's...
probably you.

11:59.620 --> 12:01.500
Katie: Look who's here, Greg --
my mother.

12:01.500 --> 12:02.750
What a surprise.

12:02.750 --> 12:05.620
Yeah, well, uh,
Greg called me and said

12:05.620 --> 12:07.920
how much you missed me,
so I just stuffed your father

12:07.920 --> 12:09.960
with the loose pills I found
at the bottom of my purse

12:09.960 --> 12:11.040
and came right over.

12:11.040 --> 12:12.420
Oh, that is
so sweet of him.

12:12.420 --> 12:14.170
Greg, can you come
in the office

12:14.170 --> 12:15.920
and help me check
on the printer toner again?

12:15.920 --> 12:17.670
Katie, I can --
We're low on magenta,
Greg.

12:17.670 --> 12:18.880
We're low.

12:22.710 --> 12:23.920
Happy Christmas.

12:23.920 --> 12:25.330
I have no idea
who you are,

12:25.330 --> 12:28.000
but I have a feeling you know
how to make a rum hot toddy.

12:28.000 --> 12:29.000
That, I do.

12:29.000 --> 12:31.120
Alright, then.

12:31.120 --> 12:33.080
Oh, my God.

12:33.080 --> 12:34.960
A meat tree?

12:34.960 --> 12:37.170
I thought I buried
that tradition with my mother.

12:38.960 --> 12:41.170
Um, what the hell, Greg?

12:41.170 --> 12:42.420
Let me explain.

12:42.420 --> 12:44.960
When I invited your mom,
it was in retaliation

12:44.960 --> 12:47.460
to you inviting my brother
without asking me.

12:47.460 --> 12:50.290
But in the meantime --
and here's the funny twist --

12:50.290 --> 12:52.500
my brother and I had
a really nice moment,

12:52.500 --> 12:54.330
and I realized
you were right.

12:54.330 --> 12:56.000
I am super mad at you.

12:56.000 --> 12:57.620
But real quick --
what am I right about?

12:57.620 --> 13:00.120
I do regret not calling
my brother for two years.

13:00.120 --> 13:03.380
My pond
needed to be mucked.

13:03.380 --> 13:04.750
Maybe yours does, too.

13:04.750 --> 13:07.920
Maybe me
revenge-inviting your mom

13:07.920 --> 13:09.080
was a good thing.

13:09.080 --> 13:11.040
I just wanted to bond
with Taylor,

13:11.040 --> 13:13.750
and now my mother
is going to ruin it.

13:13.750 --> 13:16.250
In the future, leave the mucking
to the professionals.

13:16.250 --> 13:17.540
[ Piano plays ]

13:17.540 --> 13:20.830
♪ You better watch out,
you better not cry ♪

13:20.830 --> 13:24.330
♪ You better not pout,
I'm tellin' you why ♪

13:24.330 --> 13:25.420
♪ Santa Claus... ♪

13:25.420 --> 13:27.920
Wow.
He plays the piano, too.

13:27.920 --> 13:30.080
He has a very sad,
lonely life.

13:30.080 --> 13:32.790
♪ Santa Claus is comin' ♪

13:32.790 --> 13:37.920
♪ To toooooooooooown ♪

13:37.920 --> 13:39.040
[ Laughter ]

13:39.040 --> 13:41.040
What a nice Christmas
this is turning out to be.

13:41.040 --> 13:43.040
I'm just thrilled to be
with family this year.

13:43.040 --> 13:45.620
Kathryn: Oh, Greg,
your brother is fabulous.

13:45.620 --> 13:47.920
Why did it take you two years
to get in touch with him?

13:47.920 --> 13:49.670
Pardon?

13:49.670 --> 13:52.000
Yeah, yeah,
two years ago Thanksgiving,

13:52.000 --> 13:53.540
Greg's mother let it slip

13:53.540 --> 13:55.750
that his dad
had a second family.

13:55.750 --> 13:58.330
Ugh.
It was so uncomfortable.

13:58.330 --> 14:00.250
And everybody
was miserable.

14:00.250 --> 14:01.710
I loved it.
[ Chuckles ]

14:02.670 --> 14:04.830
You knew about me
two years ago

14:04.830 --> 14:06.290
and never thought to call?

14:06.290 --> 14:07.290
It's complicated, Greg.

14:07.290 --> 14:09.580
You lied to me, Greg.

14:09.580 --> 14:11.920
That makes you
no better than Dad.

14:11.920 --> 14:13.250
Uh, I need some air.

14:15.080 --> 14:16.420
Kathryn: Ooh.

14:16.420 --> 14:17.920
[ Door opens ]
This could give
that Thanksgiving

14:17.920 --> 14:19.620
a run for its money.
[ Door closes ]

14:19.620 --> 14:22.330
Now I see why you didn't want
your mother here for Christmas.

14:22.330 --> 14:24.670
Wait, w-- You --
You didn't want me here?

14:24.670 --> 14:26.750
Then why did he call me
and say that you did?

14:26.750 --> 14:28.420
He invited you here
to get back at me

14:28.420 --> 14:31.580
for inviting his brother
without asking him.

14:31.580 --> 14:34.290
Oh, so this was
a spite invite?

14:34.290 --> 14:37.420
Just for that,
I am staying for two weeks.

14:37.420 --> 14:39.710
I didn't know you didn't
want to see your brother,

14:39.710 --> 14:41.790
but you knew I didn't
want to see my mother.

14:41.790 --> 14:43.670
[ Scoffs ]
I'm staying three weeks,

14:43.670 --> 14:45.080
and I'm wearing
the shorty robe.

14:45.080 --> 14:46.170
[ Gasps ]

14:46.170 --> 14:49.710
♪♪

14:53.380 --> 14:55.420
♪♪

14:55.420 --> 14:56.830
[ Both sigh ]

14:56.830 --> 14:59.040
There goes the drama-free
Christmas we wanted.

14:59.040 --> 15:00.620
Worst part is,
it's all our fault.

15:00.620 --> 15:04.040
Should've just gotten
you the flashlight
I saw on Facebook.

15:04.040 --> 15:06.000
It also can break a windshield
if you drive into a lake.

15:06.000 --> 15:07.080
Smart.

15:07.080 --> 15:10.500
I'm gonna go out front
and wait for my brother.

15:10.500 --> 15:11.920
You go deal with your mom.

15:11.920 --> 15:14.210
Why are the holidays
about family?

15:14.210 --> 15:16.330
Why can't it just be
about Chinese food

15:16.330 --> 15:17.960
and going to the movies?

15:17.960 --> 15:19.210
Should we become Jewish?

15:19.210 --> 15:20.420
I don't know. Maybe.

15:20.420 --> 15:21.540
Ehh.

15:27.540 --> 15:28.670
[ Katie sighs ]

15:28.670 --> 15:30.170
[ Door closes ]

15:30.170 --> 15:31.170
Hi, Mom.

15:31.170 --> 15:33.210
I get it.
You hate me.

15:33.210 --> 15:35.580
Is it because I missed
most of your birthday parties?

15:35.580 --> 15:37.880
Or because I made out with
your boyfriend in high school?

15:37.880 --> 15:39.670
Because I told you --
Mom, I know.

15:39.670 --> 15:41.710
He kissed you, and you were
just being polite.

15:41.710 --> 15:42.830
Exactly.

15:42.830 --> 15:44.330
You're making this
very hard for me

15:44.330 --> 15:46.120
to say I'm sorry
about all this.

15:46.120 --> 15:48.670
Well, why didn't you want me
to come to Christmas Eve dinner?

15:48.670 --> 15:49.880
I knew you would
get in the way

15:49.880 --> 15:51.710
of me doing my thing
with Taylor.

15:51.710 --> 15:53.670
You tend to be
somewhat judgmental.

15:53.670 --> 15:54.960
Oh, stop it.
I --

15:54.960 --> 15:56.290
[ Sniffs ]

15:56.290 --> 15:58.330
Oh. Where'd you get this wine?
The car wash?

15:58.330 --> 16:00.000
[ Chuckles ]

16:00.000 --> 16:01.620
I see.

16:01.620 --> 16:03.170
Building this with Taylor
this year

16:03.170 --> 16:05.420
was just too important
for you to mess up.

16:05.420 --> 16:06.920
Well, why is this year
so important?

16:06.920 --> 16:09.540
Because next year,
she's going off to college,

16:09.540 --> 16:11.960
and this is
her last Christmas at home.

16:11.960 --> 16:13.290
So? She'll be back.

16:13.290 --> 16:15.250
I told you I'd come back,
and I never did.

16:15.250 --> 16:16.710
Yeah, but why would you
come back?

16:16.710 --> 16:19.170
I mean, I was a terrible mother.
You're not.

16:19.170 --> 16:21.420
You take an interest
in Taylor's life.

16:21.420 --> 16:23.790
[ Sighs ]
She'll be back.

16:27.170 --> 16:28.290
You think?

16:28.290 --> 16:29.580
Trust me.

16:30.790 --> 16:34.960
Uh...my Spam angel
isn't exactly turning out.

16:34.960 --> 16:36.710
Don't worry about it.

16:36.710 --> 16:38.620
Meat tree is off.

16:38.620 --> 16:39.710
Yes!

16:39.710 --> 16:41.000
You're the best mom.

16:41.000 --> 16:43.880
How about we start a new
tradition that's not nauseating?

16:43.880 --> 16:46.500
Something that the three of us
can do together.

16:46.500 --> 16:47.500
Really?
Mm-hmm.

16:47.500 --> 16:48.830
We could build
a snowman.

16:48.830 --> 16:50.250
I don't think
Grandma wants to stand

16:50.250 --> 16:51.540
out in the freezing cold,
honey.

16:51.540 --> 16:53.880
Actually, Grandma has
her own holiday tradition

16:53.880 --> 16:55.290
that keeps her
very warm.

16:55.290 --> 16:56.330
[ Chuckles ]

16:56.330 --> 16:57.620
Mm.

16:57.620 --> 16:59.330
What are we gonna do
with this?

16:59.330 --> 17:03.380
♪♪

17:03.380 --> 17:04.500
[ Whimpers ]

17:04.500 --> 17:07.830
Even he thinks
it's gross.

17:07.830 --> 17:10.670
It's not Christmas
without Nana's platter, Mom.

17:10.670 --> 17:12.080
That's what
I went upstairs for.

17:12.080 --> 17:13.170
Thank you, sweetie.

17:20.290 --> 17:21.330
[ Gasps ]

17:23.790 --> 17:25.170
What the hell?

17:25.170 --> 17:28.210
That platter survived
two world wars

17:28.210 --> 17:31.170
and Lee Majors'
Christmas Bacchanalia.

17:31.170 --> 17:33.290
[ Both sigh ]

17:33.290 --> 17:36.120
I can't believe
I did this.

17:40.920 --> 17:43.080
Mom,
it wasn't your fault.

17:43.080 --> 17:44.960
You didn't break the platter.
We did.

17:44.960 --> 17:46.750
Anna-Kat:
We glued it back together,

17:46.750 --> 17:48.670
but we didn't let it dry
long enough.

17:48.670 --> 17:51.290
I can't believe
the two of you did this.

17:51.290 --> 17:54.170
Anna-Kat was there, but I
convinced her to cover it up.

17:54.170 --> 17:56.500
Oliver, you are in
so much troub--

17:56.500 --> 17:58.830
To be fair, Mom,
all you wanted for Christmas

17:58.830 --> 18:01.880
was for us to get along,
and...

18:01.880 --> 18:04.120
look at us.

18:04.120 --> 18:06.960
So you're saying you worked
together to deceive me,

18:06.960 --> 18:08.380
and that's how
you got along?

18:08.380 --> 18:10.500
Merry Christmas.
Merry Christmas.

18:10.500 --> 18:12.380
Okay.

18:12.380 --> 18:16.420
But because of this,
you two are going to repair it

18:16.420 --> 18:18.380
so that Taylor
can inherit it.

18:18.380 --> 18:20.960
You seriously don't have
one piece of jewelry to give me?

18:20.960 --> 18:22.710
Mnh-mnh.

18:22.710 --> 18:30.500
♪♪

18:30.500 --> 18:32.120
It's pretty cold out here
for a walk.

18:32.120 --> 18:33.710
You've been gone
a while.

18:33.710 --> 18:35.500
"Blow, blow,
thou winter wind,

18:35.500 --> 18:39.170
thou art not so unkind
as man's ingratitude."

18:39.170 --> 18:40.540
I deserve that.

18:40.540 --> 18:43.210
Nothing stings quite as much
as a good Shakespearean burn.

18:44.420 --> 18:46.040
I'm sorry I didn't try
and find you

18:46.040 --> 18:48.170
as soon as Dad told me
I had a brother.

18:48.170 --> 18:50.330
I think I was still
angry with him,

18:50.330 --> 18:52.710
and I took it out
on you.

18:52.710 --> 18:54.460
Yeah, I can see that.

18:54.460 --> 18:55.880
Now that I've met you,
I understand

18:55.880 --> 18:57.460
why he never approved
of anything I did.

18:57.460 --> 19:00.790
He had another son
he approved of -- you.

19:00.790 --> 19:02.580
That's not really
the truth, Greg.

19:02.580 --> 19:04.790
I was sent away to
boarding school when I was 7.

19:04.790 --> 19:07.330
Dad saw me
two weeks a year.

19:07.330 --> 19:09.290
I now realize
that's 'cause he was here

19:09.290 --> 19:10.960
the rest of the year --
with you.

19:10.960 --> 19:14.170
He was, but he took
absolutely no interest in me.

19:14.170 --> 19:15.330
Ah.

19:15.330 --> 19:17.000
So I guess
we were both neglected,

19:17.000 --> 19:19.330
just in different ways.

19:19.330 --> 19:20.960
It's funny --
you're the only other person

19:20.960 --> 19:22.620
who knows what it's like
to have our father.

19:22.620 --> 19:25.330
And who knows the crazy sound
he makes after he sneezes.

19:25.330 --> 19:26.920
Both: Achoo-floo-floo!

19:26.920 --> 19:28.710
What is that?
[ Chuckling ]
I don't know.

19:28.710 --> 19:29.710
[ Sighs ]

19:29.710 --> 19:31.830
So...brothers?

19:31.830 --> 19:33.540
Ah, brothers.

19:33.540 --> 19:34.830
[ Grunts ]

19:34.830 --> 19:35.920
[ Chuckles ]

19:35.920 --> 19:37.580
I think it's time
we show these kids

19:37.580 --> 19:39.120
how to have
a real snowball fight!

19:39.120 --> 19:40.710
Come on, American Greg!

19:43.540 --> 19:45.120
So, Dad never taught you
to throw a ball, either?

19:45.120 --> 19:46.750
No, he did not.
Mm.

19:46.750 --> 19:48.120
Let's get 'em!

19:48.120 --> 19:50.790
[ Laughter, screaming ]

19:50.790 --> 19:53.670
♪♪

19:53.670 --> 19:57.500
[ Laughter ]

19:57.500 --> 19:58.500
It is?
Mm-hmm.

19:58.500 --> 19:59.750
Thank you.

19:59.750 --> 20:01.790
[ Laughter ]

20:01.790 --> 20:05.500
♪♪

20:05.500 --> 20:07.040
You want
to cock it back...

20:07.040 --> 20:09.710
Okay.
...step, throw.

20:09.710 --> 20:12.790
[ Indistinct talking ]

20:12.790 --> 20:14.210
[ Camera clicks ]

20:14.210 --> 20:17.710
♪♪

20:17.710 --> 20:20.460
When everyone's asleep,
let's add our gifts to Santa's.

20:21.460 --> 20:22.670
Now that I have
a brother,

20:22.670 --> 20:24.620
we have so much brother stuff
to catch up on.

20:24.620 --> 20:28.830
I'm glad that you're excited
that you have a brother.

20:28.830 --> 20:29.960
I am.

20:29.960 --> 20:31.710
I'm glad
you mucked in my pond.

20:31.710 --> 20:32.830
Thank you, honey.

20:32.830 --> 20:34.170
Uh, quick question.

20:34.170 --> 20:37.250
I know that Taylor is,
but is Oliver of drinking age?

20:37.250 --> 20:39.080
None of the kids
are old enough to drink.

20:39.080 --> 20:40.750
Right.

20:40.750 --> 20:42.500
I knew that.

20:42.500 --> 20:44.040
Kids, bad news!

20:44.040 --> 20:45.170
Ugh.

20:45.170 --> 20:47.710
Next time, Greg,
just drown me in the pond.

20:51.580 --> 20:53.750
♪ Hark! The herald angels sing ♪

20:53.750 --> 20:56.670
♪ "Glory to the newborn King ♪

20:56.670 --> 20:59.330
♪ Peace on Earth
and mercy mild ♪

20:59.330 --> 21:02.330
♪ God and sinners reconciled" ♪

21:02.330 --> 21:05.330
♪ Joyful, all ye nations rise ♪

21:05.330 --> 21:08.580
♪ Join the triumph
of the skies ♪

21:08.580 --> 21:11.330
♪ With angelic hosts proclaim ♪

21:11.330 --> 21:14.330
♪ "Christ is born
in Bethlehem" ♪

21:14.330 --> 21:16.670
♪ Hark! The herald a-- ♪

21:18.330 --> 21:19.330
Oliver.

21:19.330 --> 21:21.710
♪♪
